social_posts.post_text: It’s finally time to switch roles 😉 Happy wedding day @lindseyfrerichs ❤️ So excited for you to begin this next chapter of life! #marryingmills

Just a little life update. I had a small ankle surgery last week to address an injury I sustained in May while racing at Pre.  Everything has gone really well so far and I was already able to start some light cross training this week.  I have an amazing team helping me navigate all of this and feel confident we are working toward a fun and much healthier 2023! ⚡️

Guess who got to start some bike workouts and new ankle rehab exercises! 🙋🏼‍♀️ 
•
Being home for the holidays often requires some flexibility with training and today was one of those days. Winter weather tried to interfere with my plane for training today when the gym I normally use in Springfield closed for the day. Thankfully @paigeallisonbrashears and @spfld_sc came to the rescue with the perfect space and equipment for today’s training session! 🙌🏻
A little snapshot of the last two weeks. Lots of fun, adventures, and quality time spent with family and friends (and a little training in there too). 🥰

Six years ❤️ Can’t think of a better person to have by my side for the last six years (especially during the roller coaster that 2022 was 🥴). I feel so lucky to have found the perfect partner to take on life! 🥰

At little look at training the last few weeks! I’m now five weeks post-op and (hopefully 🤞🏻) getting close to running on ground! Taking this much time off running has been a challenge, but I’ve been working hard to embrace what I can do and make the most out of each step I get to make. 
•
While I haven’t been logging many miles in my @garminrunning watch, I’ve still been relying on it for the training I am doing! I’ve found it incredibly helpful to monitor my heart rate throughout my cross training to ensure I’m making the most out of it! Plus the watches can track so much more than just running which means it all loads on to my @garminclipboard account for my coaches to see. 🤩
•
Let me know if you guys would be interested in more about some of the specifics of the cross training I have been doing! ⚡️ #comebackszn #garminsponsored

Today was a big day!! First run on ground and at full body weight! 🤩🤩 Lots of snow in Flagstaff meant day one had to be on the treadmill, but the excitement levels were high regardless! Very happy with the progress my ankle is making and thankful for the team I have helping me with this comeback! ⚡️

I’m normally not a fan of strides 😝 but yesterday was a different story! 🤩 Slowly adding more and more each week! ⚡️ 
•
📸: @jt.productions_

Last month I had the honor of standing by my sister as she made the most beautiful bride and fulfilled our mom’s dream of marrying her high school sweetheart 🥰😜 (In all seriousness though, I’m so happy to have Dawson officially part of the family!) I couldn’t be more excited for Lindsey and Dawson to begin this journey and I’m so thankful I got to be a part of the day ❤️ 📸: @alysonkayphotography

Patience. This is the word I have been coming back to a lot recently. I have been feeling really good in my comeback and things have been progressing really well which has me so eager to keep doing more. My PT, Colleen (@strength.is.speed ), who is thankfully writing my return because we know I would have overdone things if left on my own, keeps reminding me to be patient as we build back to continue giving my ankle the best chance to heal and avoid setbacks. 
•
Because of this, we have been slowly adding the running back which means I’ve still been doing a lot of cross training. I am up to five days of running (outside and alter G), but today was one of my bike only days. Cross training has been a new thing for me, but I have tried to really embrace it which is helping me stay present with my training. Something that has really helped with that is modeling my bike workouts after my track workouts. This helps me to envision what kind of effort I should be doing. One of my favorites so far has been a longer tempo effort (15-20 min) followed by speed endurance type reps (60 sec reps off 30 sec rest). Fingers crossed I’ll be back on the track doing these workouts soon, but for now you’ll find me focused on being patient and enjoying each step I get to make! 🤞🏻⚡️ 
•
📸: @joshthomson

First hour long run this morning, followed by some longer strides! Nothing fancy, but my body is feeling ready to start building up the mileage and add in workouts! 🤩 anyone else feel like strides at altitude are the hardest thing?! 🫣

10 weeks later and I’m finally back! 🤩 First workout today and I could not stop smiling. It wasn’t anything flashy, but it felt so good to feel the legs and lungs burning and to push myself. I know I have a lot of work ahead of me, but I’m ready to keep taking steps toward healthy training and racing! ⚡️

Oof the road back to fitness is humbling…but the burn feels so good at the same time! Another workout in the books ✅ Gotta love when the @garminrunning watch says productive for the day! ⚡️ #comebackszn #garminpro

Asked Elise what song she wanted to get ready for workouts and this was her answer for the entire altitude camp 😂 Flagstaff threw us some curveballs with more snow than I’ve ever seen before, but that didn’t stop us from having a good time and getting a little running in there as well 😜
Not quite cleared to start hurdling yet, so going back to the basics! Oregon was showing off with some beautiful weather today as well 🤩

Accurate depiction of training in March…a mix of joy, challenge, and tiredness. Slowly stacking weeks and enjoying the process of seeing progress each week. The fatigue definitely started to hit this week, but thankfully I was monitoring my @garminrunning app and realized the volume had quickly added up. Spending the last day of March taking a much needed rest day to set myself up for another month of building in April! ⚡️ #comebackszn #garminpro
Felt a little rusty to start, but we are back in business! Making more progress toward #steepleszn 🤩⚡️

Working both ends of the pace spectrum today….threshold work followed by some fast running! My body is feeling healthy so we have started to add some speed back in to keep working on improving my turnover. Anyone else have to work extra hard on the speed like me?! ⚡️ #comebackszn
Hurdling my way through hump day! 🐪 Feeling more and more like myself each week! 🤩

Day by day, brick by brick ⚡️ 
•
📹: @dillonvibes

Ripped the bandaid off and toed the line on Friday night for the first time in 8 months to get my 2023 season started. Nothing flashy, but my body felt the strongest and healthiest it has in a long time. And at only 5 months post-surgery, that is the biggest win I could ask for! ⚡️ #comebackszn 
•
📸 1,2: @runjwill 
📸 3: @shelbyisland

Gotta love that “good day at the office” feeling! 🤩 Coming back from surgery has had lots of ups and downs, but everyday has been filled with gratitude for being healthy again! ⚡️
•
📸: @hellobrigit
Blue skies, my favorite trail in Park City, and my new @garminrunning Forerunner 265 made for the perfect run this morning! 🤩 So happy to be back training at altitude! 🏔️ #beutahful #garminpro

Happy Global Running Day! Running has brought me so much more than I could have ever imagined- some of the most important relationships in my life and the opportunity to see the world and represent my country. Through the highs and lows, the ability to run everyday and push myself to my potential is such a gift! Hope everyone had a chance to celebrate today! 🏃🏼‍♀️❤️ #globalrunningday #garminrunner
Great day at the office brought by the summer sun and the best company! 🥰 (just missing @teenbean505 ❤️) #solarpowered

Happy Olympic Day!! ❤️🤍💙 I don’t think my 8 year old self would ever believe the journey I’ve been on since I dreamt of competing in the Olympics one day…but I wouldn’t change it for anything. Never forget to keep dreaming!
Set a practice PR this week, but forgot to start my watch which means I have no proof in my @garminrunning app 😩 Training has been coming together nicely and I’m excited for USAs next week! 🤩

Well, this isn’t a post I ever imagined making, but I unfortunately will not be lining up for tonight’s final. Shortly after cooling down from Thursday’s prelim I started to experience a lot of pain in the ankle I had surgery on. Things progressed yesterday to the point walking alone become painful. We aren’t exactly sure what happened, but running a steeplechase right now is unfortunately out of the equation. I am incredibly sad as my team and I have worked so hard to get me back to the starting line this year, but I know making decisions around being healthy for next year has to remain the priority. I am hopeful it is just a bad sprain and I will be able line up for some races later this season. Thank you all for the continued support and I look forward to getting back out there soon.

Me trying to figure out when the roller coaster that’s been the last year and a half is going to end 🥴
•
Just wanted to give a little injury update. Following US Champs we decided to get more imaging done to figure out what was causing me so much pain in my ankle. The good news is the injury I had surgery for is doing well. However, I managed to have a new injury with two torn ligaments and a bone bruise in my fibula. We assume this happened when I fell during the prelim at USAs, but I’m still a bit confused as I have very little memory of what actually happened when I fell (adrenaline is wild 😳). I am very happy to report it is improving a lot and I have been cleared to start running again.  I’m also not ready to give up on having some sort of a season quite yet, so I am heading to Europe to continue training with my team in hopes of getting in some races in August and September. The last year and a half has been extremely trying with so many health issues and injuries, but I’m confident if I keep prioritizing listening and learning to trust my body again, I’ll find my confident self back on the starting line. I’m immensely grateful for all those in my corner as well, that have worked so hard to help me through all of this!
A much needed reset in England with some dear friends over the weekend ❤️ So thankful to have such amazing people in my life all over the world.

While I love that I have been able to use my Garmin for all my cross training, I’m so happy I’m back using it for my favorite activity! Got to put the flats on today for a couple strides 🤩 My ankle is feeling better and better and I can’t think of a better place to be to get back to training! 🏃🏼‍♀️❤️🏔️ #ontopoftheworld #garminpro

Back to work on one of my favorite tracks! 🤩 First track workout since USAs was a success! Even got to do some repeats in spikes 🙌🏻 Excited to keep putting more work in and hopefully get in some racing soon! ⚡️ 
•
📸: @ilariafedeli66

Slowly hitting my stride again and most importantly, finding so much joy in the process of it!⚡️🏃🏼‍♀️
•
📸: @michaeldawson.nz

A little glimpse into the last four weeks 🥰
•
Finally heading down from the mountains to start some racing. I came to St. Moritz with no plan and a lot of uncertainty if I would be able to get back to racing this season. While my current plan is very far from my plan A, B, or even C, it’s a plan that has given me the opportunity to remember why I do this in the first place. Injuries and illnesses throughout the last year and a half have left me with a lot of distrust in my body’s ability to run and race at this level, but this time has afforded me an incredible chance to focus on just that- finding trust in my body, joy in my running, and taking things day by day. Sometimes life looks very different than you expect, but it can end up being an opportunity you didn’t know you needed. ⚡️

1 week, 2 races, 5 cities, and 52 miles….and I never had to recharge my @garminrunning Forerunner 265 😱 (I started with a full charge Monday and it’s still at 21% today!!). It was a very busy week with travel and racing 🤩 so I’m very thankful I can always count on my Garmin to keep track of all my miles along the way! #garminpro

Weekend in Scotland recap: raced a mile on the track for the first time in 10 years at the @mileclassic 😱, lots of quality sister time exploring Edinburgh, and finished with a lovely dinner with our fav Scot 🥰

Jumped into an 800 with some speedy friends today followed by a visit to the Olympic Park for the first time since 2017 World Champs 🤩 10/10 day 🥰

After 7 weeks in Europe, finally made it back across the pond for my last race of the season, the Fifth Avenue Mile! Last little tune up workout this morning and the legs are feeling good and ready to go! 🏃🏼‍♀️⚡️

Fun-filled weekend in the Big Apple including a Lobo reunion, time with family, finding all the best gf spots in NYC, my first show on Broadway, and the opportunity to toe the line with an incredible group of athletes at the Fifth Avenue Mile! A big thanks to @nyrr for taking such good care of us athletes and providing the perfect event to end the season! ⚡️

All of us have experienced it.

Self-doubt. Uncertainty. Lack of belief.

That’s ok. That’s normal.

But what’s also normal is knowing where you BELONG.

Knowing that you’re not just showing up to take part. You’re showing up to take over!

Our BELONG bracelet is a special collaboration with @courtneyfrerichs  that dates back to the Tokyo Olympic Games where she wore a small temporary tattoo that said belong as a reminder that she belonged on the starting line and when she began to take the lead in the race, she belonged there!

Let our BELONG bracelet ft. Courtney remind you where you belong!

I’ve spoken a lot about this, but I’m a huge believer in the power of mantras. I use them throughout training and racing and they often change depending on what I am wanting to focus on or struggling with. In 2021, I made a decision to prioritize my mental health as I started to really see the impact it was having on my running. During the work with my therapist that year, we kept coming back to the same word, belong. Throughout the season, the word had become so impactful that I decided to wear a temporary tattoo that said belong on my wrist for the final of the Tokyo Olympic Games- a reminder to myself that I belonged in that race. As I made my move to take the lead in the race, I repeated the word in my head over and over, a reminder that I belonged. This resulted in my best race result to date- an Olympic silver medal. 
•
For the last few years, @artiken has been amazing and created a bracelet at the start of each year with my current word or mantra. Following that race, I knew I had to have one that read, “belong.” They later reached out about a full collaboration and I was over the moon. Because belong isn’t just about running- it’s about knowing you belong on whatever path you want to be on. Belong has continued to be such an impactful word for me that I actually had it permanently tattooed- a reminder to myself of that night in Tokyo.  I am so excited to share this with you all and hope it helps you guys as much as it has helped me. 🥰🌸
Much needed long weekend in Mexico filled with sister time, relaxation, amazing food, and lots of time in the water and sun! 🤩🌴☀️🏖️
Found a familiar face in Nixa 🫣 Such an honor to be included in the downtown mural in my hometown!

Meet Courtney at the Health and Fitness Expo presented by @bluecrossblueshieldkc on Friday, October 20th at 12:30 pm. Courtney will be pacing the 1:30 half marathon group on race day.
Took the scenic route home so I could enjoy my post run latte with a view! 🤩 Fall in the mountains is definitely my favorite! 🍁

So excited to be back in the Midwest with @garminrunning for the @kcmarathon weekend! The KC running community holds such a special place in my heart and I love getting to be a part of this weekend 🩵 Come find me in the 1:30 half marathon group tomorrow! 💙🩵

Quick, but very fun-filled weekend in Kansas City! Griff took second in the marathon behind friend and UMKC teammate, Jason. My mom ran her first 10k and killed it! We had a roounion 🦘 I had the opportunity to help out a big crew of runners in the half-marathon 🤩 And can’t forget the pre-race ice cream! The KC running community is a special one and I feel so grateful to get to be a part of the @kcmarathon weekend thanks to @garminrunning 🩵💙
Well that was fast. And fun. Thanks to all who raced, paced, helped and cheered at the Garmin @kcmarathon! #GarminAmbassador @courtneyfrerichs
Back to work! 💪🏻 First week of workouts and my body is feeling healthy and strong, which is all I can ask for! Excited to keep building for the 2024 Olympic year! 🤩

Sun’s out in November in Oregon?! Had to take advantage of it with a workout out on the bike path today! Slowly building a strong foundation, week by week 🤩 
•
PS, very thankful for the opportunity from @nyrr to race this weekend, but unfortunately will not be toeing the line. I am healthy and things are going well ‼️ just need to focus on training right now- best of luck to everyone in NYC this weekend!

Not much to show for November other than some @garminrunning data, but I’ve been stacking weeks and finding a consistency in training I haven’t seen for almost two years. My body is healthy and there has been a joy in my training that has been missing for a long time! Here’s to carrying this momentum in to the last month of 2023! 🤩

One year later- running healthy and strong! ✨
•
I met with my surgeon last month to check in on things (all good things to report!) and as we discussed how things had been going throughout the year post surgery, he told me “well this year will be that much better because you won’t be coming back from surgery.” I had always heard it can take a good year to feel back to normal following a surgery, but as I hit the year mark, he has been spot on.  There has been so much learning that has taken place throughout the last 12 months, but the biggest lesson is that your brain’s trust in your body is not only the most important factor, but the piece that takes the most time and patience. 
•
It’s certainly been a journey, but I have full belief I am coming out the other side stronger. Here’s to tackling the upcoming year with the trust that my body knows how to handle hard things! And if you are in the middle of the post-surgery/injury journey now, there are better days ahead; take it day by day and surround yourself with a team that believes in you! 🩵

7 years ❤️
•
Celebrated 7 years of marriage today in the best way possible- a long run together followed by brunch 🥰
•
2023 you were quite the doozy…but I’m so thankful to have had Griffin by my side through it all. Here’s to making 2024 and year 8 our best year yet! ❤️

2024- a year of change. 
•
After seven years, my time with the Bowerman Track Club has come to an end. This chapter has given me some of the greatest moments of my running career and some of the best relationships with teammates I will forever cherish. I have so much gratitude for the guidance Jerry, Pascal, Shalane, Colleen, and Chris have given me and their belief in me has been instrumental in the success I have had as an athlete. BTC is an incredibly special organization and I’m so thankful to have had the opportunity to be a part of it. I don’t think my 23 year old self could have ever imagined the journey that this chapter would be. 
•
I am immensely grateful for the support I have received from @nikerunning and very excited to continue my partnership with them along with @garminrunning as we enter an exciting Olympic year! 
•
@griffinhumphreys has begun assisting Amy and Alistair Cragg and their team. They have offered their guidance in my training and their athletes have welcomed me with open arms. I am also so happy to be reconnecting with Pascal in the pursuit of becoming the best steeplechaser I can be. 
•
Change is a lot of emotions- scary and sad, yet also filled with an excitement of what is to come. I feel incredibly lucky to have had and continue to have an amazing team around me and look forward to the journey ahead!
Little bit of turnover today to get the body ready for some altitude workouts! First time running on the new track @unmloboxctf 🤩 It feels so good to be back in ABQ! ⛰️🌶️
First long run at altitude this morning! Many miles were put in on this path in the lead up to the Rio Olympics and it feels so good to be back! 🤩⛰️

Last week, Courtney Frerichs announced that after seven years with the team, she has left the Bowerman Track Club. We had a chance to catch up with her and discuss the ups and downs of the past two years, her decision to leave BTC, and her new training setup.

Read the Q&A at fastwomen.substack.com or via the links in our bio and stories.
